### 3. Resolver Implementation (The Tricky Parts)

#### A. Cursor-Based Pagination Resolver
Unlike `offset/limit`, cursors (usually an encoded ID or timestamp) prevent items from being skipped if a new post is added while a user is scrolling.

```javascript
const resolvers = {
  Query: {
    feed: async (_, { first = 10, after }, { db }) => {
      let query = db.table('posts').orderBy('created_at', 'desc').limit(first + 1);

      if (after) {
        const decodedCursor = Buffer.from(after, 'base64').toString('ascii');
        query = query.where('created_at', '<', decodedCursor);
      }

      const posts = await query;
      const hasNextPage = posts.length > first;
      const nodes = hasNextPage ? posts.slice(0, -1) : posts;

      return {
        edges: nodes.map(post => ({
          cursor: Buffer.from(post.created_at.toISOString()).toString('base64'),
          node: post
        })),
        pageInfo: {
          hasNextPage,
          endCursor: nodes.length > 0 
            ? Buffer.from(nodes[nodes.length - 1].created_at.toISOString()).toString('base64') 
            : null
        }
      };
    }
  },

  Post: {
    // Using DataLoader to prevent N+1
    author: (post, args, { loaders }) => {
      return loaders.userLoader.load(post.authorId);
    },
    likesCount: (post, args, { loaders }) => {
      return loaders.likeCountLoader.load(post.id);
    }
  }
};
```

